events.originalText: Rioting broke out in Antananarivo, Madagascar, sparking a political crisis that led to the deposal of President Marc Ravalomanana.
events.subtitle: Antananarivo
events.headline: Rioting in Antananarivo, Madagascar leads to President Ravalomanana's ousting

events.originalText: An earthquake in the Indian state of Gujarat killed at least 13,000 people, injured 167,000 others and destroyed nearly 400,000 homes.
events.subtitle: 2001 Gujarat earthquake
events.headline: Gujarat earthquake claims 13,000 lives and destroys 400,000 homes

events.originalText: In a nationally televised press conference, U.S. president Bill Clinton denied having "sexual relations" with intern Monica Lewinsky.
events.subtitle: Bill Clinton
events.headline: Bill Clinton denies affair with Monica Lewinsky in televised press conference

events.originalText: Somali Rebellion: Factions led by the warlord Mohamed Farrah Aidid and his rebel group, the United Somali Congress, ousted President Siad Barre.
events.subtitle: Somali Rebellion
events.headline: Somali Rebellion ousts President Siad Barre led by Mohamed Farrah Aidid

events.originalText: Turkish Airlines Flight 301 crashed while taking off from İzmir Adnan Menderes Airport, killing 67 people.
events.subtitle: Turkish Airlines Flight 301
events.headline: Turkish Airlines Flight 301 crash kills 67 in Izmir

events.originalText: JAT Flight 367 exploded in mid-air over Czechoslovakia; the only survivor of the 28 on board, flight attendant Vesna Vulović, fell 10,160 m (33,330 ft), setting the record for surviving the highest fall without a parachute.
events.subtitle: JAT Flight 367
events.headline: JAT Flight 367 explosion over Czechoslovakia with one survivor falling 10,160m

events.originalText: The three Beaumont children disappeared from a beach in Glenelg, South Australia, resulting in one of the country's largest-ever police investigations.
events.subtitle: Disappearance of the Beaumont children
events.headline: Beaumont children disappear from Glenelg beach in South Australia

events.originalText: Spontaneous anti-British riots erupted in Cairo following the killings of 50 Egyptian auxiliary police officers the previous day.
events.subtitle: Cairo fire
events.headline: Anti-British riots in Cairo after killing of 50 Egyptian police officers

events.originalText: Indian independence movement: India became a republic under a new constitution, with Rajendra Prasad as president and Jawaharlal Nehru as prime minister.
events.subtitle: Indian independence movement
events.headline: India becomes a republic with Rajendra Prasad as president and Jawaharlal Nehru as PM

events.originalText: The Hale Telescope at Palomar Observatory (pictured) in California, the largest aperture optical telescope in the world for 28 years, saw first light.
events.subtitle: Hale Telescope
events.headline: Hale Telescope at Palomar Observatory sees first light in California

events.originalText: Audie Murphy engaged in action at the Colmar Pocket that won him a Medal of Honor and made him one of the most famous and decorated U.S. soldiers of World War II.
events.subtitle: Audie Murphy
events.headline: Audie Murphy wins Medal of Honor at Colmar Pocket in World War II

events.originalText: A group of Red Guards hung a red lantern atop the tower of the Helsinki Workers' House, symbolically marking the start of the Finnish Civil War.
events.subtitle: Red Guards (Finland)
events.headline: Red Guards hang red lantern marking start of Finnish Civil War

events.originalText: The 3,106-carat (621 g) Cullinan Diamond (pictured), the largest gem-quality rough diamond ever found, was discovered at the Premier Mine in Gauteng, South Africa.
events.subtitle: Carat (mass)
events.headline: Cullinan Diamond, largest gem-quality rough diamond, found in South Africa

events.originalText: Commodore Gordon Bremer took formal possession of Hong Kong Island for the United Kingdom at Possession Point.
events.subtitle: Gordon Bremer
events.headline: Commodore Gordon Bremer takes possession of Hong Kong Island for UK

events.originalText: William Bligh, the governor of New South Wales, was deposed in the only military coup in Australian history.
events.subtitle: William Bligh
events.headline: Governor William Bligh deposed in only military coup in Australian history

events.originalText: Captain Arthur Phillip and the British First Fleet landed at Sydney Cove on the shore of Port Jackson in present-day Sydney, establishing the first permanent European settlement in Australia.
events.subtitle: Arthur Phillip
events.headline: British First Fleet lands at Sydney Cove, establishing first European settlement in Australia

events.originalText: An earthquake with a moment magnitude of around 9.0 occurred off the Pacific Northwest coast of North America, as evidenced by Japanese records of tsunamis.
events.subtitle: 1700 Cascadia earthquake
events.headline: 9.0 magnitude earthquake off Pacific Northwest coast triggers tsunamis

events.originalText: Livonian War: A Lithuanian surprise attack resulted in a decisive defeat of numerically superior Russian forces.
events.subtitle: Livonian War
events.headline: Lithuanian surprise attack defeats Russian forces in Livonian War

events.originalText: The Council of Trent officially separates Roman Catholicism and Protestantism
events.subtitle: Council of Trent
events.headline: Council of Trent officially separates Roman Catholicism and Protestantism
